### 16.4 `JwtAuthenticationFilter.java` — THE BOUNCER (Full Actual Code)

```java
package com.example.inventory.security;

import jakarta.servlet.FilterChain;
import jakarta.servlet.ServletException;
import jakarta.servlet.http.HttpServletRequest;
import jakarta.servlet.http.HttpServletResponse;
import org.slf4j.Logger;
import org.slf4j.LoggerFactory;
import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;
import org.springframework.security.authentication.UsernamePasswordAuthenticationToken;
import org.springframework.security.core.context.SecurityContextHolder;
import org.springframework.security.core.userdetails.UserDetails;
import org.springframework.security.web.authentication.WebAuthenticationDetailsSource;
import org.springframework.util.StringUtils;
import org.springframework.web.filter.OncePerRequestFilter;

import java.io.IOException;

public class JwtAuthenticationFilter extends OncePerRequestFilter {
    // ↑ OncePerRequestFilter = Runs exactly ONCE for every HTTP request
    //   Even if a request passes through multiple filters, this runs only once

    private static final Logger logger = LoggerFactory.getLogger(JwtAuthenticationFilter.class);

    @Autowired
    private JwtUtils jwtUtils;
    // ↑ Injected: the JWT utility for validating/parsing tokens

    @Autowired
    private CustomUserDetailsService userDetailsService;
    // ↑ Injected: loads user details from database

    @Override
    protected void doFilterInternal(HttpServletRequest request,
                                    HttpServletResponse response,
                                    FilterChain filterChain) throws ServletException, IOException {
        // This method runs for EVERY HTTP request to the backend

        try {
            // ─── STEP 1: Extract token from request header ───
            String jwt = parseJwt(request);
            // Looks for: "Authorization: Bearer eyJhbGci..."
            // Returns: "eyJhbGci..." (just the token part)
            // Returns null if no Authorization header or doesn't start with "Bearer "

            // ─── STEP 2: Validate the token ───
            if (jwt != null && jwtUtils.validateJwtToken(jwt)) {
                // Token exists AND is valid (good signature + not expired)

                // ─── STEP 3: Extract user email from token ───
                String username = jwtUtils.getUserNameFromJwtToken(jwt);
                // Decodes the JWT payload → gets the "subject" field (email)

                // ─── STEP 4: Load full user info from database ───
                UserDetails userDetails = userDetailsService.loadUserByUsername(username);
                // Queries: SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = ?
                // Returns: UserDetails with email, hashed password, roles

                // ─── STEP 5: Create Spring Security authentication ───
                UsernamePasswordAuthenticationToken authentication =
                        new UsernamePasswordAuthenticationToken(
                            userDetails,                    // The user object
                            null,                          // No credentials needed (already validated)
                            userDetails.getAuthorities()); // User's roles (ROLE_USER, etc.)

                authentication.setDetails(new WebAuthenticationDetailsSource().buildDetails(request));
                // Attaches request metadata (IP address, session ID)

                // ─── STEP 6: Set user as "authenticated" for this request ───
                SecurityContextHolder.getContext().setAuthentication(authentication);
                // From this point, Spring Security considers this request AUTHENTICATED
                // Controllers can access the user via SecurityContextHolder.getContext().getAuthentication()
            }
            // If jwt is null or invalid → SecurityContext remains empty → user is NOT authenticated

        } catch (Exception e) {
            logger.error("Cannot set user authentication: {}", e.getMessage());
            // If anything goes wrong, user stays unauthenticated
        }

        // ─── STEP 7: Pass request to next filter / controller ───
        filterChain.doFilter(request, response);
        // Whether authenticated or not, the request continues
        // The SecurityFilterChain (in SecurityConfig) will check if authentication is required
    }

    // ─── HELPER: Parse JWT from Authorization header ───
    private String parseJwt(HttpServletRequest request) {
        String headerAuth = request.getHeader("Authorization");
        // Reads: "Authorization: Bearer eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiJ9..."

        if (StringUtils.hasText(headerAuth) && headerAuth.startsWith("Bearer ")) {
            return headerAuth.substring(7);  // Remove "Bearer " (7 characters) → just the token
        }
        return null;  // No valid Authorization header found
    }
}
```

**When this filter runs — for every request:**
```
Request: GET /api/products
Header: Authorization: Bearer eyJhbGci...xyz

Filter steps:
1. parseJwt() → extracts "eyJhbGci...xyz"
2. validateJwtToken() → checks signature & expiry → true
3. getUserNameFromJwtToken() → "user@email.com"
4. loadUserByUsername("user@email.com") → User from DB
5. Create Authentication object with roles
6. SecurityContextHolder.set(authentication) → REQUEST IS NOW AUTHENTICATED
7. filterChain.doFilter() → passes to SecurityConfig's rules → allowed → reaches controller
